 1. Executive Summary
Elevate Payment Partnerships (EPP) — also known internally as 'Control Our Destiny' (COD) and the 'Bank Independence Program' — was a multi-year strategic initiative at PayPal/Braintree designed to dramatically reduce dependency on third-party banks and payment processors. At its core, EPP was about Braintree acquiring the capability to own and control its end-to-end payments stack: from transaction processing through dispute management, financial events, and merchant reporting.
The initiative was anchored in two critical business imperatives. First, Wells Fargo — Braintree's primary acquiring bank at the time — had begun limiting the types of merchants it would support, specifically declining to continue servicing crypto, NFT, and high-risk merchant categories. This put Braintree in a vulnerable position where a third party was dictating which merchants it could serve. Second, competitors like Adyen and Stripe were already operating on BIN Sponsorship and self-processing models, giving them vastly superior control, speed-to-market, and operational efficiency.
The EPP initiative migrated merchants in carefully sequenced phases from the Wells Fargo pipeline onto a new stack built around Fiserv as the processor and Goldman Sachs (later Pathward for high-risk) as the acquiring bank. The Disputes team — specifically the Arbiter platform — was tasked with building a completely new end-to-end integration with Fiserv's dispute management system, covering chargeback ingestion, merchant notification, financial events, representment submission, reporting, and monitoring.
This document captures the complete story of that work: the why, the what, the how, the blockers encountered, the architectural decisions made, the data analysis performed, and the operational playbooks created along the way.
 2. Background and Strategic Context
2.1 Braintree's Processing Model Before EPP
Prior to EPP, Braintree processed payments primarily through an ISO (Independent Sales Organization) model, which industry analysts considered a legacy approach by 2022-2023 standards. Under this model, Braintree was fully dependent on third-party acquiring banks and processors for the entire payment lifecycle. The primary bank was Wells Fargo (WFMS — Wells Fargo Merchant Services), and disputes flowed through the Wells CashMan/DFM (Data File Manager) system.
This dependency created significant constraints. Any product improvement, new merchant capability, or operational change required alignment with and execution by the third-party bank. Latency in dispute file delivery, limited visibility into dispute status, and inability to onboard certain merchant categories were all symptoms of this dependency. When Wells Fargo decided it would no longer support crypto and NFT merchants, it exposed the existential risk of this model: a third party could effectively determine Braintree's addressable market.
2.2 Competitive Landscape
The strategic urgency behind EPP becomes clear when viewed against the competitive backdrop. Adyen and Stripe — Braintree's primary competitors in the enterprise payments space — had already moved to a mix of BIN Sponsorships and self-processing models. These companies owned their technical stack end-to-end:
•	They could go to market in new countries without third-party approval or delays.
•	Monitoring, support, and remediation of operational incidents could be done proactively.
•	They could onboard any merchant category they chose to accept.
•	Their dispute management, reporting, and reconciliation systems were internally controlled.
Braintree continuing on the ISO model meant an accelerating capability gap versus these competitors. EPP was the answer to closing that gap.
2.3 The Vision
The long-term vision of EPP was to create a redundant, scalable, and competitive processing and post-processing platform for Braintree, PayPal, and Venmo merchants. The ultimate north star — beyond the immediate phases — was to connect directly with card schemes (Visa, Mastercard) for both incoming and outgoing dispute events, eliminating the intermediate processor layer entirely for dispute management.
The intermediate milestone was the Fiserv integration: Braintree would now receive dispute data directly from Fiserv via a Snowflake-based data pipeline (rather than waiting for file drops from Wells), and submit representments directly to Fiserv via their eResponse SFTP mechanism.
 3. Problem Statement
The disputes team documented two core problems that EPP was solving from a disputes management perspective:
3.1 Third-Party Dependencies
Braintree, PayPal, and Venmo were highly dependent on third-party acquiring and processing relationships. Items such as latency, product improvements, and post-processing capabilities — including reporting, disputes, and money movement — were contingent on the health and capabilities of those partners. Partners could also limit the types of merchants that Braintree could onboard (e.g., real money gaming, crypto, and other high-risk verticals), directly constraining market share and scope. The Wells Fargo situation with crypto/NFT merchants was the most visible manifestation of this risk.
3.2 Competitive Disadvantage
Braintree's ISO model was considered a legacy model by industry standards. Competitors like Adyen and Stripe completely owned their technical stack. They did not rely on — and were not blocked by — third-party processors or banks. This gave them the ability to proactively monitor, support, and remediate operational incidents, and to quickly go to market in new countries and with new product features — advantages Braintree simply could not replicate under the existing model.
3.3 Dispute-Specific Problems Being Solved
From a Braintree Disputes perspective, the specific problems EPP aimed to solve included:
•	Dependency on Wells Fargo's DFM file (delivered daily via SFTP, subject to Wells' SLAs)
•	No ability to independently control reply-by date calculations or SLA enforcement
•	Limited transparency into dispute lifecycle updates — Fiserv's Snowflake model offered real-time access vs. Wells' batch file model
•	Inability to onboard certain high-risk merchant categories, costing Braintree addressable market (e.g., Coinbase, real money gaming)
•	Financial events (debits/credits to merchants) were dependent on third-party funding pipelines with limited reconciliation visibility
•	Reporting was fragmented — merchants used multiple SFTP-based custom reports that had known reconciliation issues
