4.1 The Post-Pivot (March 31, 2023)
A critical inflection point was the EPP Pivot of March 31, 2023. Originally, Phase 1B and Phase 2 were planned to go through IPP (PayPal's Instrument Processing Platform) → Fiserv → Pathward. Post-pivot, Braintree moved to integrate directly with Fiserv, cutting out IPP as an intermediary. This had significant implications for the disputes team: instead of receiving dispute data indirectly through IPP's existing file-based mechanism, Braintree would now query Fiserv's Snowflake instance directly. The Phase 1B/2 disputes confluence document was copied from the Phase 4 doc on 5/24/2023 to reflect this new reality.
4.2 Dual Pipeline Reality (Transition Period)
A particularly complex aspect of the transition period was that merchants would have disputes on BOTH the Wells pipeline and the new Fiserv/Pathward pipeline simultaneously. Braintree had to continue processing existing Wells disputes with no interruption while also handling new Fiserv disputes for migrated merchants. This dual-pipeline operation required careful strategy engine design to avoid collisions, duplicate dispute creation, and incorrect financial events.
 5. Phase 1 — Crypto/NFT Merchants (Wells → IPP/Worldpay)
5.1 Context and Merchants
Phase 1 was specifically scoped to migrate three NFT/Crypto merchants off of Wells Fargo Merchant Services (WFMS) onto Worldpay via IPP by end of March 2023. These merchants were:
Merchant Account Token	Merchant Public ID	Dispute Count (2022)
coinbaseinc_instant	k7htn4dptfgm95ct	101,937
PaniniAmerica_instant	5ytry64hrnrsgwnn	10,634
StockX_NFT	w6vcnykz4pvzrskv	57

Coinbase was by far the largest — with nearly 102,000 disputes in 2022 alone — making it the most operationally complex merchant to migrate. The high dispute volume was driven by the nature of crypto transactions: while cryptocurrency-to-cryptocurrency transfers are irreversible, credit card purchases of cryptocurrency remain fully subject to chargebacks. This creates an inherent asymmetry where the merchant (Coinbase) could disburse crypto that cannot be recovered, yet still face a chargeback on the card side.
5.2 Dispute Architecture Considerations for Phase 1
Phase 1 surfaced several dispute-specific considerations that would carry through the entire EPP program:
•	Evidence submission flow: In addition to the merchant's evidence file, Arbiter generates a 'frontmatter' file to capture transaction details for stronger rebuttal. Questions were raised about IPP supporting multiple evidence files per dispute.
•	Chargeback lifecycle alignment: Concerns were raised about how chargeback lifecycle events from Worldpay/IPP would align with Wells events, especially for StockX which had disputes on both platforms during the transition.
•	Dispute financial events: Ensuring debits and credits to merchants were accurately reflected across both pipelines was a critical requirement.
•	Data for DFR/DFIR reports: The IPP chargeback file frequency and format needed to be confirmed to ensure reporting continuity.
•	ACH return disputes: It was unclear whether IPP supported ACH return disputes, requiring clarification.
•	Cutover timing: What would happen to disputes on Wells for transactions that had already moved to IPP? Would IPP support incoming disputes for Wells-originated transactions?
5.3 Operational Requirements Raised
A formal requirements table was developed for Phase 1, covering items across two dimensions — Operational Requirements and Functional Requirements. Key items included:
•	DONE: Access to OP Back Office tool (https://www.omnipaygroup.com/ramtool) for manual evidence submission and retrieval.
•	OPEN: Worldpay to review chargebacks for validity before passing to Braintree (pre-screening). This was identified as high priority — without it, Braintree would need to 'eat' costs from incorrectly filed chargebacks.
•	OPEN: Support for expired pre-arbitration auto-acceptance (to prevent progression to arbitration). Existing logic for Wells was already in place.
•	OPEN: Chargeback spec lacked Visa RDR (Rapid Dispute Resolution) and MasterCard Ethoca alerts — high priority item requiring alternative sourcing.
