6.5 E2E Flow and Testing Framework
The team documented a comprehensive end-to-end flow for Phase 1B/2, with 10 numbered steps covering the complete dispute lifecycle:
1.	Cardholder initiates dispute — External / Issuer dependency
2.	Fiserv ingests dispute and provides data in Snowflake. Fiserv cutoff 7PM EST; data ready by 9AM EST the following day. Snowflake 'Trigger' table updated to signal readiness.
3.	BT Disputes pulls dispute data from Snowflake. Phase 1B: Chargebacks only. Phase 2: Retrievals, Pre-Arbs, Chargebacks. Phase TBD: Arbitrations.
4.	BT Disputes implements controls to ensure data integrity of records pulled from Snowflake.
5.	Note: Merchants continue to have disputes on both Wells AND Pathward during transition. BT must process existing Wells disputes with no interruption alongside Pathward disputes.
6.	Strategies create new disputes and update existing disputes in Arbiter.
7.	Merchants notified of new cases and updates via emails and webhooks (Sendgrid).
8.	BT Funding notified to initiate a debit or credit based on the dispute record. Acknowledgement received from Funding.
9.	Accurate dispute data provided for BT Reporting. Includes Dispute Report (DLR) and Dispute Financial Impact Report (DFIR). Funding handshake signals that dispute data is ready for processing.
10.	When merchant is ready to respond: evidence curation, validation, and submission to Fiserv. Auto-acceptance for RDR flag disputes. Auto-contestation if refund detected and case value > $30.
11.	BT monitors submissions to Fiserv via eResponse and receives acknowledgement once representment is processed.
A formal testing matrix was also defined, covering all components across: Ingestion (Snowflake Trigger Table, Chargebacks Table, Task), Creation (Strategies for Open/Reopen/Win/Lose/PRE), Financial Events (Debit/Credit/Fee), Representment (CP/SDK/GraphQL/Eresponse), and Reporting (CP reports, DFR, DDR, SFTP, Custom).
 7. Phase 4 — Large Enterprise BT Merchants
7.1 Target Audience and Rationale
Phase 4 targeted the top Large Enterprise (LE) and Mid-size BT merchants — those processing $8M+ in yearly TPV — moving them from Wells Fargo onto Fiserv → Goldman Sachs. The business case for focusing on these merchants was stark:
•	Top 4% of merchants generate 96% of TPV
•	Bottom 96% of merchants make up only 4% of TPV
The remaining 96% of long-tail SMB BT merchants would be migrated to PPCP (PayPal Commerce Platform) rather than the new Fiserv stack.
Phase 4 merchants were characterized as extremely low-margin merchants whose primary dispute-related goals were: (1) decreasing chargeback ratio to stay below excessive chargeback monitoring program thresholds, (2) protecting revenue through higher win rates, and (3) achieving operational excellence through seamless dispute management. Specific strategies included Dispute Automation, Standardization, Integration with Risk Portfolio products, Dispute Analytics/Data Management, Low-margin Reconciliation, and Cost Optimization.
7.2 Phase 4 Scale vs. Earlier Phases
Phase 4 represented a significant step-up in scale and complexity. Rather than 1 merchant (Phase 1B) or ~450 merchants (Phase 2), Phase 4 involved approximately 1,000 of Braintree's largest and most demanding merchants — merchants with teams dedicated to dispute management, sophisticated reconciliation requirements, and very low tolerance for any degradation in dispute handling quality.
7.3 Additional Requirements for Phase 4 vs. Phase 1B/2
Phase 4 shared the same core MVP requirements as Phase 1B/2, but added several items that were out-of-scope for earlier phases:
•	Direct Connect to Card Schemes — Phase 4+ (Out of scope for Phase 4 MVP)
•	MasterCard Ethoca Alerts — On Fiserv's roadmap for late Q3 2023; out of scope for Phase 4 MVP. Follow-up question: would this be supported for Wells during the transition period?
•	Arbitration Case Creation — Merchants should be able to see arbitration cases filed by issuing banks (nice-to-have, not MVP)
•	Dispute History — Full dispute history per case number (nice-to-have, to be revisited)
7.4 Deprecating Wells Fargo
A key output of Phase 4 was the full deprecation of the Wells Fargo pipeline. The tentative timeline was that all volume needed to be off Wells by September 30, 2024, after which BT would receive 180 days of residual traffic (including disputes). Post-cutover, the following could be deprecated:
•	Wells (WFMS) and DFM (Data File Manager) integrations in Arbiter
•	Visa RDR allowlist logic in Funding (which was originally a Wells-specific workaround)
•	Any Wells-specific codepaths in strategy engine, runners, and ingest logic
Importantly, deleting these integrations was designed to NOT impact the ability to view historical Wells disputes, CashMan records, or DFM records.
 8. Technical Architecture — EPP Phase 4 RFC
The EPP Phase 4 RFC (Request for Comment) was authored by Carla Garcia Dimanche (Anchor/Lead Engineer) and represented the definitive technical blueprint for the Fiserv disputes integration. It covered five major subsystems: Ingest, Handling, Representment, Reporting, and the Funding Handshake. The RFC also proposed two architectural improvements — splitting ingest from handling and enabling preemptive transaction lookup — that would benefit the integration long-term.
Jira Epic: DTBTCD-1169. Related components: Arbiter, Gateway, Funding, Reporting, Airflow, Datalake.
8.1 Ingest Architecture
8.1.1 Data Source Decision
A key early decision was the data source for Fiserv dispute records. Two options were evaluated: (1) Connect directly to and query Fiserv's Snowflake instance, or (2) receive a CLX (ClientLine) file likely via SFTP. The decision was to use Snowflake, with the critical architectural note that Arbiter would NOT connect directly to Snowflake. Instead, a Snowflake task would query the Fiserv data and copy the results to an S3 bucket, which Arbiter would then read from. (The original plan for direct Snowflake connectivity was marked as CANCELLED in the engineering hub — EM was originally going to create application credentials.)
8.1.2 Snowflake to S3 Pipeline
The Snowflake pipeline worked as follows: On date D, a Snowflake task queries for all chargeback records with an upd_dt (status_date) of D-1, copies results to S3 bucket bt-production-arbiter-processor-files/fiserv/chargeback/<status_date>/, and Arbiter's FileProcessor then reads and processes that file. The Snowflake task and procedure were defined in the snowflake-terraform repo.
Snowflake environments:
Environment	Snowflake Share	Purpose
Production (Goldman/Pathward)	FISERV_FISERVGBSPROD_PPDEBIT_SHARE.PPFISERV	Production data for Phase 4 and Phase 1B/2
Dev/QA (Wells data)	FISERV_FISERVGBSPROD_PPDEBIT_SHARE.BRAINTREE	Test share using Wells data for development
Snowflake UI	braintree.snowflakecomputing.com/console	Direct query access; credentials from EM David Miller

8.1.3 Ingest Runner Design
The Fiserv::ProcessorRecordIngestRunner was designed to be kicked off by a cron job daily. It orchestrates: calling Fiserv::Client to retrieve records → iterating through records → building Fiserv::ProcessorRecord objects → persisting to the fiserv_processor_record table in Arbiter's DB → either triggering Gateway TransactionLookupEvent or queueing HandleProcessorRecordJob.
Model validations were required in accordance with expected data shape. Any record with missing or unexpected data would raise a ProcessorRecordException (PRE). Separate models and DB tables were needed for retrieval records vs. chargeback records since they are separate entities in Fiserv's Snowflake.
8.2 Splitting Ingest and Handling
A key architectural improvement proposed in the RFC was to cleanly separate processor record ingest from handling. Prior to this work, ingest and handling occurred inline in a single runner. The new design:
12.	Ingest Runner retrieves records, creates/persists ProcessorRecord objects
13.	For each record: either triggers Gateway transaction lookup OR queues HandleProcessorRecordJob
14.	Gateway transaction lookup response processed via ArbiterDisputeMessageService → queues HandleProcessorRecordJob
15.	HandleProcessorRecordJob passes record to HandleProcessorRecordService for full handling
This separation moved ingest, transaction lookup, and handling into separate workers, improving performance and operational clarity. The improvement would benefit all processor integrations, not just Fiserv.
8.3 Preemptive Transaction Lookup
The RFC also proposed cutting over to preemptive Gateway transaction lookup for Fiserv disputes. Under the old (non-preemptive) model:
•	Open processor record arrives → Arbiter creates a Dispute in pending state (internal only, not visible to merchants)
•	Arbiter kicks off Gateway transaction lookup
•	Gateway returns transaction info → pending Dispute transitions to open state and becomes visible
Under preemptive transaction lookup:
•	Ingest kicks off Gateway transaction lookup BEFORE handling the open processor record
•	When Gateway returns transaction info → Arbiter creates Dispute directly in open state
•	Dispute is immediately visible to merchants with all necessary information
•	No confusing 'pending' state ever exists
Two known gaps in the existing preemptive transaction lookup implementation needed to be resolved before cutover:
16.	Auto-acceptance evaluation logic was not in place for preemptive flow. Needed to be added in DisputeBuilder — feasible because preemptive disputes are created in open state and can immediately transition to auto-accepted.
17.	Open processor records for escalated cases (open chargeback-with-retrieval or open pre-arbitration) don't undergo Gateway transaction lookup (info already retrieved). This meant open notifications weren't being created for these Disputes. Root cause: notification creation was skipped in DisputeBuilder for preemptive lookup Disputes because certain attributes aren't available until transaction lookup completes. Solution: persist dispute attributes from Gateway response on the TransactionLookupEvent so they can be accessed in DisputeBuilder without needing a live lookup.
8.4 Handling — Strategy Engine
The strategy engine was the heart of Arbiter's dispute processing. For the Fiserv integration, four handling flows were defined:
Flow	Trigger	Key Actions
Open record — new case	Open retrieval OR open chargeback with no prior retrieval	Transaction lookup → Create Dispute (open) → Evaluate auto-acceptance → Create notifications → Send financial events to Funding
Open record — escalated dispute	Open chargeback-with-retrieval OR pre-arbitration	No transaction lookup needed → Same as above (lookup already done for prior lifecycle stage)
Win or loss record	Terminal status record for existing dispute	No lookup → Transition dispute to won/lost → Create won/lost webhook → Send financial events to Funding
Update record	Non-terminal update for existing dispute	No lookup → Update dispute details (reason, amount, etc.) — no terminal state change

Required strategy classes: Fiserv::CreateRetrievalStrategy, Fiserv::CreateChargebackStrategy, Fiserv::WinDisputeStrategy, Fiserv::LoseDisputeStrategy, Fiserv::UpdateDisputeStrategy, and a no-op strategy for unactionable records. PREs would be raised for any record where no strategy or multiple strategies matched.
A shadow dispute mechanism was also built: before go-live, the team could run Fiserv shadow strategies against real Fiserv records to validate behavior without creating live disputes for merchants. This allowed identification of strategy gaps, PRE patterns, and common lifecycle sequences before full cutover.
8.4.1 Visa RDR (Rapid Dispute Resolution)
An important nuance in the handling logic was Visa RDR. RDR disputes are automatically resolved by Visa before a chargeback is formally filed. Under the Wells integration, the team had implemented a blanket allowlist approach: all Visa chargebacks for merchants on the RDR allowlist had fees waived. The Fiserv integration enabled a more granular approach: the pre_dispute_program field on ArbiterDisputeMessages could be used to waive fees on a dispute-by-dispute basis, rather than a blanket per-merchant waiver. This logic would live in both Funding and Pricing teams.
8.5 Representment Architecture
When merchants submit evidence for a dispute (or when auto-submission is triggered), Arbiter needed to submit that evidence to Fiserv. The design leveraged the existing Wells/FirstData representment architecture:
•	Fiserv::EvidenceSubmissionService created to handle evidence compilation and submission via SFTP to Fiserv's eResponse mailbox. Fiserv confirmed BT would use existing mailbox NAGW-XBMDK006 with transmission job RCDMBPSS. A new eResponse Group ID would be assigned.
•	Fiserv::DisputeAcceptanceService for cases where merchants choose to accept a dispute rather than fight it. Acceptance method: Dispute::AcceptanceMethod::FIRST_DATA_VIA_FDR.
•	DisputesReadyToExpireQuery and ExpiredRunner: if a merchant hasn't responded by the reply-by date, the dispute is transitioned to expired. Auto-submit logic for qualifying Fiserv disputes (refunded, amount > $30) was added to ExpiredRunner — mirroring existing Wells behavior.
•	DisputesReadyToLoseQuery and LostRunner: if a dispute hasn't reached terminal state after a specified period, it's transitioned to lost. Note: Fiserv confirmed all disputes eventually receive terminal status records via Snowflake, so this was primarily a safety net.
•	Evidence recommendations CSV was audited and updated for Fiserv reason codes via a mapping exercise.
8.6 Funding Handshake
A key requirement for the integration — and for enabling the reporting team to generate accurate daily reports — was implementing a 'Funding Handshake': a signal that ingest and handling for the day was complete and that financial events had been reconciled.
The design was a Datalake view (implemented via an Airflow DAG) that told Reporting four things:
18.	Is the day's processing file completed?
19.	Do the number of financial events in Arbiter and Funding match?
20.	Do the amounts of financial events in Arbiter and Funding match?
21.	Are there any unresolved PREs for the day's records?
This was modeled after a similar approach used by the Pricing team. The Datalake was chosen over EDL/BigQuery because migration to EDL would be a long process and the Pricing team was only pushing for BigQuery to support BFIT consumers. The team could proceed with Datalake for the foreseeable future.
8.7 Monitoring Strategy
The team designed a comprehensive monitoring approach using Datadog (with version-controlled dashboards), the Disputes Panel, and Splunk. Key desired metrics:
•	How long does ingest take? Are records available at the expected time?
•	How long does Gateway transaction lookup take?
•	How long does Funding acknowledgement of financial events take?
•	How long does representment take? How long does Fiserv's ACK of representments take?
•	Errors across entire flow: ingest runner failures, HandleProcessorRecordJob failures, PRE rates, EvidenceSubmissionJob/DisputeAcceptanceJob failures
Specific Jira tickets were created to: add Fiserv as a source to the Disputes Panel, fix PRE access in the Disputes Panel, and build a Datadog dashboard covering all EPP KPIs.
