 9. Data Architecture — Snowflake Integration and Field Mapping
9.1 The DFM (Data File Manager) and Snowflake
Fiserv's dispute data was originally delivered to partners via a DFM (Data File Manager) file — a CSV/structured file containing chargeback records. For the EPP integration, Fiserv exposed this data via a Snowflake share instead, allowing for more timely access and direct querying. The table was CHARGEBACK_PPFISERV_V1 (later CHARGEBACK_PPDEBIT_V1 for the Pathward/Goldman scope).
9.2 DFM Data Analysis — Dispute Lifecycle Research
Before building the integration, the team did significant data analysis on historical Coinbase dispute records from 2022 (via the Wells CashMan database) to understand the range of dispute lifecycle patterns they would need to handle. In 2022 alone, 21 different dispute lifecycle sequences were observed for Coinbase.
Three major patterns were documented and questions sent to Fiserv (via Tyler Baldwin, FiServ Research and Business Analysis Professional):
22.	82,689 cases had the sequence: [Credit to merchant / Dispute Amount debit] → Open a dispute. Question: Should these cases expect a close event at some point? (Needed to verify records hadn't had close events outside the query time boundary.)
23.	17,691 cases had the sequence: [Credit to merchant / Dispute Amount debit, STATUS MOVED TO CLOSED] → Open a dispute, Update dispute to merchant liable (lost). Tyler confirmed: this is the last update if BT doesn't provide evidence/representment. If BT provides evidence after due date, another status update would be provided.
24.	21 cases had the sequence: [STATUS MOVED TO CLOSED] with no prior OPEN chargeback notice. Question: should there have been an open update first?
9.3 Daily Volume Analysis
To plan infrastructure capacity, the team ran queries against Coinbase's daily dispute update volumes. This analysis was critical for sizing the Snowflake task, S3 storage, and Arbiter processing capacity.
