 11. Disputes Reporting Strategy
Disputes reporting was one of the most complex and dependency-heavy workstreams in EPP. Aman Jain and Jyothi Srirangam (Reporting) were specifically called out in the product documents as key stakeholders to align on this plan. The strategy was built around a deliberate short-term/long-term approach, acknowledging that the ideal end-state (DDR and DFR replacing all legacy reports) could not be achieved in lockstep with EPP merchant migrations.
11.1 Report Landscape
Five reports were in scope:
•	Dispute Financial Impact Report (DFIR) — Control Panel distribution; reports all financial events throughout dispute lifecycle; limited to Braintree-funded merchants. Grey color code.
•	Disputes Lifecycle Report (DLR) — Control Panel distribution; details all stages of dispute lifecycle; merchants use it to track disputes; available to BT-funded and bank-funded cohorts. Yellow color code.
•	Disbursement & Fee Report (DFR) — SFTP distribution; used by merchants for disbursement and fee reconciliation; includes bank transfer records with payments, disputes, and fees. Blue color code.
•	Disputes Details Report (DDR) — SFTP distribution; reports all new disputes and updates; dynamic, D+1 SLA; as of 3/2023 only available to Amazon (Venmo) and Booking.com (DCC). Green color code.
•	Disputes SFTP Reports — SFTP distribution; multiple custom variants per merchant (Uber alone had 18 different reports in US); D+2 SLA; known reconciliation issues since merchants use these to infer money movement. Red color code.
